      <Abstract xml:lang="en">The first days after birth in ferrets provide a privileged view of the development of a complex mammalian brain. Unlike humans and other primates, ferrets are born with a completely smooth neocortex. Folds, neocortical regionalisation and cortico-cortical connectivity develop in ferrets during the first postnatal days. Ferrets could thus become a major animal model to investigate neocortical development. Our aim is to provide the research community with a detailed description of Ferret brain development. We have already started a project to constitute an open, collaborative atlas of the developing ferret brain, including data for 28 ferrets (4 animals per time point from P0 to adults), acquired with high-resolution MRI and diffusion tensor imaging (DTI). We have developed an open-source pipeline to segment and produce ? online ? 3D reconstructions of brain MRI data. We propose to process the brains of 16 of our specimens (from P0 to P16) using high-throughput 3D histology, staining for cytoarchitectonic landmarks, neuronal progenitors and neurogenesis. We will extend our current web-platform to include an interactive multi-scale visualisation of the microscopy data. The platform will contain tools for the online collaborative drawing of brain regions on the combined MRI and histology data. This will be used to produce the first integrated atlas of ferret brain development.</Abstract>
